ong the Silk Road dates to at least Han Dynasty China in the second century BC. Balancing a broad array of archaeological, botanical, and historical evidence, Fruit from the Sands presents the fascinating story of the origins and spread of agriculture across Inner Asia and into Europe and East Asia. Through the preserved remains of plants found in archaeological sites, Robert N. Spengler III identifies the regions where our most familiar crops were domesticated and follows their routes as people carried them around the world. With vivid examples, Fruit from the Sands explores how the foods we eat have shaped the course of human history and transformed cuisines all over the globe.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 21. Jun 2021) 0aAgriculturezAsia, CentralxHistoryyTo 1500. 0aFoodxSocial aspectsxHistoryyTo 1500. 0aGastronomyxSocial aspectsxHistoryyTo 1500. 0aGlobalizationzAsia, CentralxHistoryyTo 1500. 0aReligion and sociologyvCase studies. 0aReligionsxRelationsvCase studies. 0aReligious pluralismvCase studies. 7aHISTORY / World.2bisacsh  aagriculture across inner asia into europe.  aalmonds and apples.  aamerica.  achina and east asia.  acomprehensive.  aentertaining.  aeurope.  afood history.  afoods shaped human history.  ahan dynasty china.  aorganized trade along silk road.  aprehistoric central asia.  apreserved plants in archaelogical sites.  asecond century bc.  atea and rice.  atracks of silk road.  atransformed cuisines all over globe.  avivid.  awhere familiar crops domesticated.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2019 Englishz978311061076508iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2019z9783110664232oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE History 2019 English